== Conclusion

This study presents a low-cost, video-based method for tracking gait changes due to adjustments in prosthesis alignment. We use a free, open-source motion capture pipeline to integrate a prosthesis-specific tracking model. This system was able to track the magnitude and direction of major alignment changes (leg length, knee and ankle angles, foot progression angle), although it was not able to fully track pelvic obliquity and minimum toe clearance. While the system itself makes use of consumer-grade hardware that could be set up in a clinic, the manual labeling and training required to develop a custom model to track the prosthesis remain a barrier to clinical use. The training and integration of task-specific pose estimation models could improve robustness in clinical populations and enable quantitative motion analysis to augment prosthetist decision making during prosthesis alignment. 
